'''Alta Rockefeller Prentice''' (April 12, 1871 – June 21, 1962) was an American philanthropist and socialite. She was the third daughter of philanthropists [[John D. Rockefeller|John Davison Rockefeller]] (1839&ndash;1937) and [[Laura Spelman Rockefeller|Laura Celestia "Cettie" Spelman]] (1839&ndash;1915). Alta married attorney Ezra Parmalee Prentice (July 29, 1863 &ndash; 1955), son of Sartell Prentice (1837-1905) and Mary Adeline Isham (1838-1913), in 1901. Alta and Ezra had three children: [[John Rockefeller Prentice]] (1902&ndash;1972), Mary Adeline Prentice (1907&ndash;1981), and Spelman Prentice (1911&ndash;2000).
She founded Alta House (c. 1900), a [[settlement house]] in [[Little Italy, Cleveland|Little Italy]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]], [[Ohio]], which is named in her honor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.rockefeller.edu/bio/laura.php?printer=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-08-04 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060422054845/http://archive.rockefeller.edu/bio/laura.php?printer=1 |archivedate=2006-04-22 |df= }}</ref><ref>http://www.clevelandmemory.org/italians/partiii.html</ref>
In 1910, Alta and Ezra bought 1,400 acres (5.7 km²) of land near [[Williamstown, Massachusetts|Williamstown]], [[Massachusetts]]. Elm Tree House, the Prentices' 72-room summer home on Mount Hope Farm, was completed in 1928. In the 1930s and 1940s, several [[geneticists]] were employed by Ezra to develop more profitable farm animals, particularly [[cattle]] and [[poultry]]. At that time, Mount Hope Farm was one of the most outstanding experimental farms in the [[United States]].
Alta died in June 1962 at the age of 91. Her property was willed to [[New York, New York|New York]]'s [[Lenox Hill Hospital]]. Shortly thereafter, Elm Tree House was purchased by its current owner, [[Williams College]].
