'''Francis Preston Blair Lee''' (August 9, 1857{{spaced ndash}}December 25, 1944) was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[United States Senate]], representing the [[Maryland|State of Maryland]] from 1914 to 1917.  He was also the great-grandson of American patriot [[Richard Henry Lee]], and grandfather of former [[Governor of Maryland|Maryland Governor]] [[Blair Lee III]].  Lee was named after his maternal grandfather, [[Francis Preston Blair]].

Lee was born in [[Silver Spring, Maryland]] and attended the common schools in the area. He was the son of [[Samuel Phillips Lee]] and his wife, the former [[Elizabeth Blair Lee|Elizabeth Blair]].  He graduated from [[Princeton University]] in 1880 and from the law department of [[George Washington University|Columbian (now George Washington) University]] in 1882.  He was admitted to the [[bar (law)|bar]] of the [[District of Columbia]] and of [[Montgomery County, Maryland]] in 1883 and commenced practice in Maryland.

Lee was an unsuccessful candidate for election to the Fifty-fifth Congress in 1896.  He was, however, elected to the [[Maryland State Senate]], and served from 1905 to 1913.  In 1911, Lee ran for the position of Governor of Maryland, but lost the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nomination to [[Arthur Pue Gorman, Jr.]] (who lost to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate [[Phillips Lee Goldsborough]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-30570586.html |title=Commentary: Right time, right place for Lee |newspaper=The Daily Record |place=Baltimore |publisher=via HighBeam {{Subscription required}} |date=January 19, 2012 |accessdate=August 30, 2013 }}</ref> In 1915, he again ran for Governor and was defeated in the Democratic Primary by eventual winner [[Emerson Harrington]].

Following his defeat in the gubernatorial election, Lee was elected to the United States Senate in a [[United States Senate special election in Maryland, 1913|special election on November 4, 1913]], to fill the vacancy caused by the death of senator [[Isidor Rayner]]. Because the [[Seventeenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] had recently gone into effect, Lee became the first U.S. Senator directly elected by the people of a state under the Constitution's provisions (although other states had previously elected senators indirectly through popular elections, which were then ratified by the state legislature).<ref>[https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/common/briefing/Direct_Election_Senators.htm Direct Election of Senators]</ref> He presented his credentials to serve as senator on December 5, 1913, but he did not qualify until January 28, 1914 because the incumbent in his seat, Republican [[William P. Jackson]], claimed that "since he had been appointed under the original constitutional provision, he was entitled to hold his seat until the regularly scheduled adjournment date of the Maryland state assembly."<ref>[https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/common/contested_elections/099Jackson_Lee.htm The Election Case of William P. Jackson v. Blair Lee of Maryland (1914)]</ref>

The Senate considered Jackson's challenge but eventually rejected it and seated Lee. While senator, Lee was chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on Expenditures in the Post Office Department|Committee on Expenditures in the Post Office Department]], and a member of the [[U.S. Senate Committee on Coast Defenses|Committee on Coast Defenses]] (Sixty-third and Sixty-fourth Congresses).  He was unsuccessful in his bid for re-election in [[United States Senate elections, 1916|1916]], losing the Democratic nomination to [[David John Lewis]] (who went on to lose to [[Joseph I. France]]).

Lee resumed the practice of law after he left the Senate.  He died in [[Norwood, Maryland]] and is buried in [[Rock Creek Cemetery]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]

