'''Dirk van den Broek''' (born 27 March 1924)<ref>{{cite web|title=Dirk van den Broek|url=http://www.dirkvandenbroekhistorie.nl/geschiedenis.html|website=www.dirkvandenbroekhistorie.nl/|accessdate=20 January 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120111158/http://www.dirkvandenbroekhistorie.nl/geschiedenis.html|archivedate=20 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a [[Dutch people|Dutch]] businessman,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/reiskrant/er_op_uit/9366196/__Amsterdam_Museum_belicht_buurtwinkels__.html?sn=reiskrant|title=Amsterdam Museum belicht buurtwinkels|date=25 March 2011|work=[[De Telegraaf]]|language=Dutch|accessdate=2 April 2011}}</ref><ref name="VerschaffelCorte2005">{{cite book|last1=Verschaffel|first1=Lieven|last2=Corte|first2=E. De|title=Powerful environments for promoting deep conceptual and strategic learning|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QzaDgG98iNAC&pg=PA151|accessdate=2 April 2011|year=2005|publisher=Leuven University Press|isbn=978-90-5867-469-2|page=151}}</ref> founder of the ''Samenwerkende Dirk van den Broek Bedrijven'', one of the largest family-owned businesses in the [[Netherlands]]. The company includes [[grocery store]]s, [[travel agent|travel agencies]], [[pharmacy|drug stores]], [[liquor store]]s and various other ventures. Born in [[Amsterdam]] in 1924, Dirk van den Broek was the son of a [[farmer]]. Inspired by his mother who ran her own [[milk]] production and delivery operation from their farm, he and his wife Joukje started a small grocery store.

Dirk van den Broek was made Officer in the [[Order of Orange Nassau]] in 1990 by [[Dutch monarchy|Queen]] [[Beatrix of the Netherlands]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2011}}

Dirk van den Broek is married and has five children.

