'''Tony Di Benedetto''' is a Canadian [[entrepreneur]] who has built, operated and divested various Canadian businesses since the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=TonyDiBenedetto.ca|url=http://www.tonydibenedetto.ca|website=TonyDiBenedetto.ca|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref> Di Benedetto is [[Chief Executive Officer]] at Drone Delivery Canada, a technology firm based in [[Toronto]] that is pioneering [[Delivery drone|drone delivery]] technology for Canadian retailers, service providers and government agencies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Management Team|url=http://www.dronedeliverycanada.com/management-team/|website=Drone Delivery Canada|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>

Di Benedetto co-founded Drone Delivery Canada with his brother Paul Di Benedetto, a [[Vaughan, Ontario]] based data center [[colocation (business)|colocation]] services provider. The objective was to pioneer and develop a next-generation [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]] [[logistics]] platform to service corporate and government clients. Launched in January 2014, Drone Delivery Canada is currently engaged with leading Canadian academics and industry leaders to develop and implement this platform.<ref>{{cite news|title=Drone Delivery Canada Commercially Launches|url=http://www.dronedeliverycanada.com/news/press-releases/drone-delivery-canada-commercially-launches/|accessdate=21 March 2016|publisher=Drone Delivery Canada|date=February 2, 2015}}</ref>   Drone Delivery Canada is seeking to become the first Canadian drone company to [[Initial public offering|go public]] on a Canadian [[stock exchange]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://business.financialpost.com/midas-letter/here-come-the-drones-and-the-investment-opportunities-arent-far-behind|title=Here come the drones — and the investment opportunities aren't far behind|website=Financial Post|access-date=2016-03-21}}</ref>

Di Benedetto also holds board positions in other ventures including Data Centre Realty, a Canadian [[data centre]] design / build firm, and Di Benedetto Group, a [[real estate investment]] group. Di Benedetto has been involved in a number of other Canadian ventures include leading successful start-ups in [[managed services]], hosting, data center construction services and [[wireless broadband]] network sectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tonydibenedetto.ca/ventures/|title=Tony Di Benedetto Ventures|last=|first=|date=March 21, 2016|website=Ventures|publisher=tonydibenedetto.ca|access-date=March 21, 2016}}</ref>

In 2009, Di Benedetto launched Data Centers Canada along with his brother Paul.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 2010|title=Data Centers Canada takes the heat off cooling|url=https://www.datacentrerealty.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/DCR-Paul-Di-Benedetto-PowerStream-Energy-Business-June-2010.pdf|journal=Powerstream Energy Business Magazine|doi=|pmid=|access-date=March 21, 2016}}</ref>   In May 2013, Terago Networks, a [[Toronto Stock Exchange]] listed [[telecommunications industry|telecom]] services provider acquired Data Centers Canada.,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.datacenterdynamics.com/news/terago-buys-data-centers-canada-for-95m/78507.fullarticle|title=TeraGo buys Data Centers Canada for $9.5m|website=DatacenterDynamics|access-date=2016-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tony Di Benedetto Ventures|url=http://www.tonydibenedetto.ca/ventures/|website=tonydibenedetto.ca|accessdate=21 March 2016}}</ref>

